ce:section.ce:para:
The antibacterial activity of the CuTA and GQD/CuTA was evaluated against S. aureus and E. coli strains (Fig. 9
                        , Table 1
                        ). The control samples without the addition of antibacterial agents showed increased cell growth with many viable colonies. For both bacterial strains, when they were treated with CuTA MOF or GQD/CuTA nanocomposite, a significant reduction in viable colonies was observed. During treatment, the nanocomposite released Cu2+ and TA, which have antibacterial properties. Cu2+ ions have a high reduction potential which triggers the reduction of O2 by a single electron. This process disrupts the respiratory chain of bacteria and creates highly oxidizing reactive oxygen species. Cu2+ and reactive oxygen species then attack the cytoplasm of bacteria by breaking hydrogen bonds, solidifying proteins, destroying the DNA structure, and inhibiting the bacterial enzyme activity within cells (Gaetke and Chow, 2003; Ozcelik and Uzun, 2009; Stohs and Bagchi, 1995). As a result, the function and structure of bacteria are destroyed. Besides, TA acts as a bactericidal agent by interfering with the alteration of lipids in the outer membrane and destroying the membrane of bacterial cells (Ikigai et al., 1993). GQD/CuTA nanocomposite exhibited higher antibacterial activity against S. aureus, compared to CuTA sample. This may be due to the presence of GQDs in the structure of nanocomposite, further improving the antibacterial activity. The antibacterial activity of GQDs could be attributed to physical interactions with the bacteria and disruption of the cell membrane integrity through oxidative stress of the membrane (Kavitha et al., 2012). The results indicated that the modification of CuTA MOF with GQDs significantly increased the antibacterial efficiency of resultant nanocomposite. As shown in Fig. 9g-j, after treatment of bacterial strain with the prepared GQD/Cu2+ and GQD/TA as control samples, the number of viable colonies of S. aureus and E. coli was significantly reduced compared to control sample. This indicates that Cu2+ and TA have antibacterial properties and inhibit bacterial growth. However, they can not completely inhibit growth of bacterial agents. Consequently, combining Cu2+ and TA antibacterial agents in a metal–organic framework form and making a nanocomposite with GQDs could lead to a higher antibacterial property due to the synergistic effect of the different antibacterial agents in one nanocomposite, GQD/CuTA.
